article.headline: San Antonio gets its first win of June
article.linkText: Silver Spurs dominate Lynx, end 8-game skid
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- With Margo Dydek back in the starting lineup,
the San Antonio Silver Stars returned to the win column.

Dydek scored 13 points, grabbed nine rebounds and blocked four
shots to lead San Antonio to a 70-57 victory over the Minnesota
Lynx, breaking a franchise-record losing streak of eight games.

The 7-foot-2 center who played in the WNBA All-Star game last
year, was starting in only her third game of this season. She was
benched for most of the season by first-year head coach Dee Brown.

"With Margo blocking shots we were able to control the paint,"
Brown said. "We found out it doesn't matter who scores, rebounds
or passes the ball, it's a team effort. It was different attitude
on the court tonight."

Dydek was joined in double figures by Marie Ferdinand and LaToya
Thomas with 13 points apiece. Adrienne Goodson had 11 points and a
career-high 12 rebounds.

"It was a great team effort," Ferdinand said. "We played
together as a unit. We had three great practices this week, we got
back to training camp and the things that got us going early."

Minnesota, which has lost four of its last five games, was led
by Katie Smith with 18 points. Teresa Edwards had 13 points, and
Tamika Williams added 11 points and 11 rebounds.

"They were a team struggling and they came out ready to play,"
said Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio. "Margo Dydek has done
a great job against us. She's been the difference maker."

Trailing 37-25 at the break, Minnesota opened the second half
with an 11-2 run and cut the lead to 39-36 on a jump shot by Helen
Darling with 16:03 to play.

San Antonio responded with a 12-0 run to lead 51-36 after a
steal and breakaway layup by Toccara Williams with 12:26 remaining.

Minnesota could get no closer than 54-49 on a layup by Nicole
Ohlde with 6:59 to play. San Antonio ended the game on a 15-7 run,
with Thomas scoring five of those points.

The win by San Antonio (4-9) was its first in June, and its
second over Minnesota this season.

"Unfortunately we were on a losing streak, which I don't think
any of us have been through before," said San Antonio point guard
Shannon Johnson, who added nine points and four assists. "That
makes this win sweeter. It's just disappointing that we couldn't
have done this a long time ago."

Minnesota, which fell to 5-7 with the loss, shot poorly on the
night, connecting on only 35.5 percent.
